Author-Name:    Galor, Oded
Author-Name:  Tsiddon, Daniel
Title:   Technological Progress, Mobility, and Economic Growth. 
Journal: American Economic Review
Pages: 363-82
Issue: 3
Volume: 87
Year: 1997
Month:  June 
Abstract:
  This paper analyzes the relationship between technological progress, wage
 inequality, intergenerational earnings mobility, and economic growth. In
 periods of major technological inventions, a decline in the relative
 importance of initial conditions raises inequality, enhances mobility, and
 generates a larger concentration of high-ability individuals in
 technologically advanced sectors, stimulating future technological
 progress and growth. However, once technologies become more accessible,
 mobility is diminished and inequality decreases but becomes more
 persistent. The reduction in the concentration of ability in
 technologically advanced sectors diminishes the likelihood of
 technological breakthroughs and slows future growth. User friendliness,
 therefore, becomes unfriendly to future economic growth.   Copyright 1997 by American Economic Association.
